A list is _correct_ if and only it satisfies the following four requirements:

- The list has at least one entry
- The last entry is `b`
- Every entry with an even index is `a`
- Every entry with an odd index is `b`

```
def is_correct_entry(idx, v):
    if idx % 2 == 0:
        return v == &#39;a&#39;
    else:
        return v == &#39;b&#39;

def my_fancy_test(l):
    return l and l[-1] == &#39;b&#39; and all(is_correct_entry(idx, v) for idx, v in enumerate(l))
```

This code might have a speed advantage because it does not create new lists, avoids costly `len` computations and does not check the remainder of the list if it finds an incorrect entry (check the [documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#all) for the `all` built-in method).

